The synthetic approaches were generally straightforward. Initially, commercially available natural flavones and isoflavones were used as starting material (Scheme 2
                        ). Firstly, starting from flavones 1, 2 and 3 for instance, they reacted with various bromide substituted fatty acid esters 6a-f in the presence of K2CO3 in DMF (Scheme 3
                        ). The resulting esters 7 were then converted into hydroxamic acids 8 according to the reported method in high yield [33]. Meanwhile, using A ring of isoflavones as capping groups, natural product biochanin A (4) and formononetin (5) reacted with bromide compounds 9a-c to yield acetyl protected hydroxamic acids 10. After cleavage the acetyl group under mild acidic conditions, HDACs inhibitors 11 were delivered in almost quantity yield. Derivatives 12 from apigenin were mixed with 2-Chloroethyldimethylamine or 3-Chloropropyldimethylamine in acetone under reflux conditions to give rise to corresponding hydroxamic acid compounds. The same hydroxamic acid formation reaction was used to furnish the HDACs inhibitors 15. Compound 16, also derived from apigenin, reacted with dibromoethane and was subjected to various diamines to provide precursor 19, which was then converted into corresponding hydroxamic acid products. Finally, both compounds 15 and 20 were prepared as stable and soluble hydrochloride salts (Please find the structure of all analogues from Table 1
                        ).
